method:
Life expectancy calculations were based on abridged life table approach. Mortality data by sex and age group were extracted from annual files supplied to OHID by the Office for National Statistics (ONS). Deaths were allocated to the deceased's middle super output area (MSOA), lower super output area (LSOA) and output area (OA) of usual residence using the latest version of the National Statistics Postcode Lookup and aggregated to wards and Clinical Commissioning Groups. Deaths were allocated to local authorities and counties based on the ONS geography provided in the death dataset. Population data are mid-year population estimates for the geographical areas descibed as 'middle layer super output areas' (MSOAs), 'lower layer super output areas' (LSOAs), and 'output areas' (OAs) , by sex and single year of age, available from the ONS.Counts by single year of age were aggregated into the age groups required for the calculation of life expectancy (less than 1, 1 to 4, 5 to 9, 10 to 14, then in 5 year age bands through to 80 to 84, 90 and over).
What are output areas? The ONS produces mid-year (June) small area population estimates by Output Areas (OA). Output areas are the lowest level of geographic area specifically designed for census data. These standardised geographic areas are designed to have equal numbers of households or populations within them making it easier to compare output areas.&nbsp;
They are used primarily in statistical administrative data outputs such as the census and population estimates. Output areas are "nested" within larger geographic areas that can be summed or aggregated to provide data at these larger areas.&nbsp;
The upper age band used for the calculation of life expectancy in this dataset is 90 years and over. OA deaths and population estimates were aggregated to wards and LSOA deaths and population estimates were aggregated to MSOAs and CCGs using standard geographical lookup tables obtained from ONS Geography.

The rate gives the annual rolling rate for a given month. In this calculation, the denominator is the sum of the cases for the current month and the 11 preceeding months. The denominator is the sum of the bed days for the current month and the 11 preceeding months.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The rate for a month is then calculated by dividing the numerator by the denominator and multiplying by 100,000 to give a manageable value.

countDefinition:
All cases of&nbsp;CDI meeting the 'Definition' section above occurring for the past 11 months are summed with the current month to give a rolling 12-month total. For the calculation of rates, the past 11 months are summed with the current month and the denominator is the sum of the bed-days (for trusts) or population (for&nbsp;SICBLs) for the current month and preceding 11 months. 
&nbsp;
The rate for a month is then calculated by dividing the numerator by the denominator and multiplying by 100,000 to give a manageable value.

